{
    Luddite: {
        type: ["Interpersonal"],
        flavor: """
            <p><em>The squad's new logistics doll arrived at 0600, carrying supply crates like they weighed nothing. She smiled, introduced herself, offered to reorganize the armory. Half the squad welcomed the help. One did not.</em></p>
            <p>"We don't need it. We were handling supplies fine before."</p>
            <p>"She's just trying to help, Mack."</p>
            <p>"'Help.' Right. First it's carrying crates. Then it's running inventory. Then it's making tactical calls and we're the ones carrying crates."</p>
            <p><em>He grabbed his gear and walked out, shoulder-checking the doorframe on the way.</em></p>
            <p>"She's been here twenty minutes."</p>
            <p>"Twenty minutes too long."</p>
        """,
        description: """
            <h3>Effects</h3>
            <ul>
                <li>You believe dolls serve only to displace humans from their roles, their jobs, and eventually their relevance. Your feelings range from quiet wariness to open hostility.</li>
                <li>You gain 3 strife whenever you are forced into direct interaction with a doll (receiving orders from one, relying on one in the field, or being helped by one).</li>
                <li>The first time this anxiety applies in a scene, you gain 1 fortune point.</li>
            </ul>
        """
    },
    Dosimeter: {
        type: ["Interpersonal"],
        flavor: """
            <p><em>The new contractor arrived from a Yellow Zone outfit. Gear was clean, credentials checked out, medical clearance stamped and filed. The squad's medic pulled the Commander aside anyway.</em></p>
            <p>"Her dosimetry log shows cumulative exposure in the high twenties."</p>
            <p>"That's within tolerance."</p>
            <p>"Within tolerance <em>now</em>. What about in three months? What about when we're sleeping in the same FOB and she starts coughing at 0300?"</p>
            <p>"She passed medical."</p>
            <p>"Medical clears people who turn six weeks later. You know that."</p>
            <p><em>The Commander looked at the new arrival, who was laughing with the rest of the squad, unaware of the conversation happening twenty meters away.</em></p>
            <p>"Just... keep an eye on her readings. That's all I'm asking."</p>
        """,
        description: """
            <h3>Effects</h3>
            <ul>
                <li>You cannot stop thinking about exposure. Every cough is Early-Stage. Every headache is the beginning of the end. You watch the people around you for signs they might be carrying something they haven't disclosed.</li>
                <li>You gain 3 strife whenever you learn that someone near you has significant Collapse exposure, or whenever someone in your unit displays symptoms that could be ELID-related (even if they aren't).</li>
                <li>The first time this anxiety applies in a scene, you gain 1 fortune point.</li>
            </ul>
        """
    },
    "Eat the Rich": {
        type: ["Social"],
        flavor: """
            <p><em>The White Zone liaison arrived by private VTOL. Pressed uniform, unmarked boots, skin that had never seen UV outside a tanning suite. She stepped onto the tarmac and immediately wrinkled her nose.</em></p>
            <p>"Is there somewhere with... better air filtration? I'd like to conduct the briefing indoors."</p>
            <p><em>The squad watched from the motor pool. One of them set down a wrench, slowly.</em></p>
            <p>"She flew here. In a private aircraft. To tell us how to do our jobs."</p>
            <p>"She's the funding contact, Volya. Be nice."</p>
            <p>"She's wearing shoes that cost more than our quarterly ammunition budget. I can see it from here."</p>
            <p>"So?"</p>
            <p>"So she's never bled for anything in her life, and now she's going to stand in our house and tell us what's worth bleeding for."</p>
        """,
        description: """
            <h3>Effects</h3>
            <ul>
                <li>White Zone wealth is built on the labor and suffering of everyone outside those walls. You know it, and you can't pretend otherwise. Their charity is PR, their contracts are exploitation, and their concern for your wellbeing extends exactly as far as your usefulness.</li>
                <li>You gain 3 strife whenever you must defer to, accept aid from, or cooperate with someone whose authority derives from White Zone wealth or privilege.</li>
                <li>The first time this anxiety applies in a scene, you gain 1 fortune point.</li>
            </ul>
        """
    },
    "Quarantine Mentality": {
        type: ["Interpersonal"],
        flavor: """
            <p><em>The convoy picked up a hitchhiker outside the Purification Zone border: a woman with sun-cracked skin and a heavy pack, walking south. The driver let her ride in the back. Twenty minutes later, the squad leader found out.</em></p>
            <p>"Stop the vehicle."</p>
            <p>"What? Why?"</p>
            <p>"Where did she come from?"</p>
            <p>"She said she was heading to the Green Zone for work-"</p>
            <p>"Where did she <em>come from</em>."</p>
            <p><em>The driver hesitated.</em></p>
            <p>"She didn't say."</p>
            <p>"Then she gets out. Now."</p>
            <p>"She's just a civilian, Sarge. She's not sick."</p>
            <p>"You don't know that. You don't know where she's been, what she's touched, who she's been near. Pull over."</p>
            <p><em>The woman was left on the roadside with a ration pack and no explanation. She watched the convoy pull away without a word. She'd seen that look before.</em></p>
        """,
        description: """
            <h3>Effects</h3>
            <ul>
                <li>People from Yellow Zones and beyond are unknowns. No citizenship records, no verifiable service history, no medical baselines. They've lived in contamination alongside Paradeus recruiters and Varjager raiders, and you have no way to confirm they aren't one of them. You cannot afford to trust what you cannot verify.</li>
                <li>You gain 3 strife whenever you must work closely with, share quarters with, or depend on someone from a Yellow Zone or higher contamination area.</li>
                <li>The first time this anxiety applies in a scene, you gain 1 fortune point.</li>
            </ul>
        """
    },
    Sheep: {
        type: ["Social"],
        flavor: """
            <p><em>The Green Zone checkpoint was backed up for two hours. Everyone stood in line, ID chips pinging, waiting for the scanner to clear them through. Everyone except one.</em></p>
            <p>"Just go around. There's a gap in the fence line two blocks east."</p>
            <p>"I'm not going through a gap in the fence. That's how you get flagged."</p>
            <p>"Flagged by who? The camera that's been broken for three weeks? The guard who's asleep in the booth?"</p>
            <p>"It's not worth the risk. We wait like everyone else."</p>
            <p><em>A long, disgusted look.</em></p>
            <p>"That's exactly the problem. You wait like everyone else. You stand in line, you let them scan you, you go home to your assigned block and eat your subsidized rations and you never once ask why you need permission to exist in your own city."</p>
            <p>"It's not that bad."</p>
            <p>"It's exactly that bad. You just stopped noticing."</p>
        """,
        description: """
            <h3>Effects</h3>
            <ul>
                <li>Green Zone residents are domesticated. They traded their autonomy for surveillance, their initiative for subsidized stability, and they'll defend the arrangement because the alternative means admitting they gave up. You find their compliance unbearable.</li>
                <li>You gain 3 strife whenever you must cooperate with or rely on someone whose worldview is shaped by Green Zone complacency (defending regulations, deferring to authority without question, or dismissing risks you know are real).</li>
                <li>The first time this anxiety applies in a scene, you gain 1 fortune point.</li>
            </ul>
        """
    },
    Dissident: {
        type: ["Social"],
        flavor: """
            <p><em>The URNC liaison pinned a commendation ribbon on the squad leader's chest. Camera crews filmed from three angles. The press release was already written.</em></p>
            <p>"On behalf of the Coalition, we recognize your outstanding contribution to the Sector 9 Purification Initiative."</p>
            <p><em>Applause. Handshakes. The squad leader smiled for the cameras. One operator stood at the back of the formation, jaw tight, eyes fixed on the middle distance.</em></p>
            <p>"They're giving us a medal for the op where they sent us in without extraction support."</p>
            <p>"Keep your voice down."</p>
            <p>"Three casualties. No medevac for forty minutes. And now it's a photo op."</p>
            <p>"It's politics. Just stand there."</p>
            <p>"That's what they're counting on. That we'll just stand there."</p>
        """,
        description: """
            <h3>Effects</h3>
            <ul>
                <li>The URNC trades safety for obedience, and you see the transaction clearly. Every public initiative has a classified cost. Every regulation exists to consolidate control. Even when the Coalition does something genuinely good, you cannot stop looking for the strings.</li>
                <li>You gain 3 strife whenever you must comply with URNC directives, cooperate with Coalition officials, or accept institutional authority without challenge.</li>
                <li>The first time this anxiety applies in a scene, you gain 1 fortune point.</li>
            </ul>
        """
    },
    "Never Unarmed": {
        type: ["Mental"],
        flavor: """
            <p><em>The safehouse had a working shower. Hot water, even. The squad rotated through in pairs, fifteen minutes each. When it was her turn, the Commander walked in still wearing her plate carrier.</em></p>
            <p>"You're not seriously showering in that."</p>
            <p>"The sidearm comes off. The carrier stays."</p>
            <p>"We're in a Green Zone. Behind two checkpoints. There's a lock on the door."</p>
            <p>"There was a lock on the door in Kazan, too."</p>
            <p><em>A pause. Nobody asked what happened in Kazan.</em></p>
            <p><em>She adjusted the straps so the water could reach her shoulders, turned the faucet, and stood under the stream with her eyes open, facing the entrance. Twelve minutes later she came out, dried the carrier with a towel, and slept in it.</em></p>
            <p><em>The squad stopped commenting after the first week.</em></p>
        """,
        description: """
            <h3>Effects</h3>
            <ul>
                <li>You do not feel safe without your weapons and armor on your body. Sleep is done in kit. Showers are calculated and never fully relaxed. Social situations where weapons are inappropriate become a source of visible discomfort that others notice and remember.</li>
                <li>You gain 3 strife whenever you are required to disarm, remove your armor, or enter a situation where carrying weapons is prohibited or socially unacceptable.</li>
                <li>The first time this anxiety applies in a scene, you gain 1 fortune point.</li>
            </ul>
        """
    },
    "Manifest Destiny": {
        type: ["Interpersonal"],
        flavor: """
            <p><em>The American contractor leaned back in his chair, boots on the table, telling a story about his grandfather's unit pushing through Belarus in '49.</em></p>
            <p>"My point is, we were winning. We had Moscow on the ropes. If the home front hadn't fallen apart-"</p>
            <p>"Your home front fell apart because your government was running bioweapon experiments in South America while its own cities burned."</p>
            <p><em>The table went quiet.</em></p>
            <p>"That's... that was a different program. The Aurora thing was CIA, it wasn't-"</p>
            <p>"It was your flag. Your soldiers. Your weapons turning jaguars into ELID carriers and releasing them into civilian populations. Spare me the org chart."</p>
        """,
        description: """
            <h3>Effects</h3>
            <ul>
                <li>Americans broke the world trying to run it. Imperialism, bioweapons, abandoned allies, a civil war they started themselves. The flag changed but the arrogance didn't. You hear it every time one of them opens their mouth about how things used to be.</li>
                <li>You gain 3 strife whenever you must take orders from, rely on, or cooperate closely with an American.</li>
                <li>The first time this anxiety applies in a scene, you gain 1 fortune point.</li>
            </ul>
        """
    },
    "Red Menace": {
        type: ["Interpersonal"],
        flavor: """
            <p><em>The Neo-Soviet advisor arrived with a briefcase, a translator she didn't need, and a speech about "shared sacrifice in service of collective reconstruction." The squad listened politely. One did not.</em></p>
            <p>"Collective reconstruction. That's what they called the Railway Corps, too. Before they started loading political prisoners onto the trains."</p>
            <p>"That's not what this is about."</p>
            <p>"It's always what it's about. They dress it up different every time. 'The Union endures.' 'Suffering builds strength.' Meanwhile their own generals tried to overthrow their government twice in ten years and they act like it never happened."</p>
        """,
        description: """
            <h3>Effects</h3>
            <ul>
                <li>The Neo-Soviet Union glorifies suffering and calls it ideology. Their military committed treason at Singularity and Fireworks, their special forces nearly tore the country apart, and they exiled the dissenters to radiation trains instead of holding anyone accountable. Rossartrism is authoritarianism with better branding.</li>
                <li>You gain 3 strife whenever you must take orders from, rely on, or cooperate closely with a Neo-Soviet citizen.</li>
                <li>The first time this anxiety applies in a scene, you gain 1 fortune point.</li>
