    Isolationist: {
        type: ["Interpersonal"],
        flavor: """
            <p><em>The Japanese operator ate alone. Maintained her own gear. Filed her reports without comment. When the squad tried to include her in the evening meal, she declined politely. Every time.</em></p>
            <p>"She doesn't trust us."</p>
            <p>"Can you blame her? Her grandparents were locked in a safe zone and left to die."</p>
            <p>"That was the Americans. We're not Americans."</p>
            <p>"Doesn't matter. To her, everyone outside Japan is the same. The ones who left and the ones who watched them leave. She'll work the contract, do her part, and the second it's over she's gone. Don't take it personally."</p>
            <p>"I'm not taking it personally. I'm saying I can't rely on someone who's already halfway out the door."</p>
        """,
        description: """
            <h3>Effects</h3>
            <ul>
                <li>Japan survived by trusting no one, and every Japanese operator you've met carries that lesson like scripture. They're capable and already planning their exit before the mission starts. You can't build a team with someone whose national identity is built on the conviction that everyone else will abandon them.</li>
                <li>You gain 3 strife whenever you must take orders from, rely on, or cooperate closely with a Japanese national.</li>
                <li>The first time this anxiety applies in a scene, you gain 1 fortune point.</li>
            </ul>
        """
    },
    Eurocrat: {
        type: ["Interpersonal"],
        flavor: """
            <p><em>The Pan-European advisor had prepared a seventeen-slide presentation for a two-hour operation.</em></p>
            <p>"Slide nine covers contingency protocols for scenarios where primary extraction is delayed by more than-"</p>
            <p>"We don't need seventeen slides. We need a truck and a map."</p>
            <p>"I understand the preference for simplicity, but the PECMAR framework requires documented contingency planning for any operation exceeding-"</p>
            <p>"People are dying while you're formatting bullet points."</p>
            <p><em>The advisor adjusted her glasses, visibly composing herself.</em></p>
            <p>"The last operation that skipped contingency planning lost four operators in the first hour. I wrote that report. I know their names. Would you like to hear them, or would you like to see slide ten?"</p>
            <p>"I'd like to leave before slide ten becomes about us."</p>
        """,
        description: """
            <h3>Effects</h3>
            <ul>
                <li>Europeans won a war by committee and now they think every problem is a committee problem. Frameworks, protocols, institutional review. They'll plan the rescue mission until the hostages die of old age, and then write a report about lessons learned. Their obsession with process is a coping mechanism for a continent that keeps almost destroying itself.</li>
                <li>You gain 3 strife whenever you must take orders from, rely on, or cooperate closely with a Pan-European national.</li>
                <li>The first time this anxiety applies in a scene, you gain 1 fortune point.</li>
            </ul>
        """
    },
    "Fair-Weather": {
        type: ["Interpersonal"],
        flavor: """
            <p><em>The Yugoslavian fixer had connections everywhere. URNC supply officers, black market brokers, Rossartrist sympathizers, anti-Rossartrist militias. She could get anything. The squad used her constantly. One member kept count.</em></p>
            <p>"She sold ammunition to the same people who were shooting at us last month."</p>
            <p>"She's a fixer. That's what they do."</p>
            <p>"She sold ammunition. To the people. Shooting at us."</p>
            <p>"And now she's selling us ammunition. Circle of life."</p>
            <p>"What happens when someone offers her more than we're paying? Because someone will. And she'll take it. That's what they always do. Belgrade didn't survive by picking a side. It survived by selling to both."</p>
        """,
        description: """
            <h3>Effects</h3>
            <ul>
                <li>The Balkans survived by playing every side of every conflict simultaneously, and the people who grew up there learned the lesson too well. Loyalty is transactional. Allegiance is temporary. A Yugoslavian will work with you, for you, and against you in the same week if the price is right. You can't trust someone whose national survival strategy is principled fence-sitting.</li>
                <li>You gain 3 strife whenever you must take orders from, rely on, or cooperate closely with a Yugoslavian.</li>
                <li>The first time this anxiety applies in a scene, you gain 1 fortune point.</li>
            </ul>
        """
    },
    "Charity Case": {
        type: ["Interpersonal"],
        flavor: """
            <p><em>The North African engineer rebuilt the squad's water filtration unit in under an hour with salvaged parts. It worked better than the original. The squad leader filed a commendation. Someone in the back muttered.</em></p>
            <p>"Great. Now we owe them a favor."</p>
            <p>"We don't owe anyone anything. She fixed the filter."</p>
            <p>"And next week it's 'we fixed your filter, so lend us your transport.' Then it's 'we need medical supplies, remember the filter.' Every interaction is an investment. They've been running that play since the colonial pullout."</p>
            <p>"Or she just fixed the filter because it was broken."</p>
            <p>"Nobody from the NAU does anything for free. They can't afford to. That's not an insult, it's arithmetic."</p>
        """,
        description: """
            <h3>Effects</h3>
            <ul>
                <li>North Africa was colonized, bombed, colonized again, and then left with the bill. You've watched them turn survival into a negotiation tactic so refined it looks like generosity. Every favor is leverage. Every act of competence is a down payment on a future ask. You respect the hustle. You refuse to be part of it.</li>
                <li>You gain 3 strife whenever you must take orders from, rely on, or cooperate closely with a North African.</li>
                <li>The first time this anxiety applies in a scene, you gain 1 fortune point.</li>
            </ul>
        """
    },
    Bystander: {
        type: ["Interpersonal"],
        flavor: """
            <p><em>The Australian medic was good at his job. Calm under fire, steady hands, solid trauma care. Nobody questioned his skills. But around the campfire, after the third round, someone always brought it up.</em></p>
            <p>"Must be nice. Growing up somewhere the Collapse didn't touch."</p>
            <p>"It touched us. Trade collapsed. Refugees-"</p>
            <p>"Your trade collapsed. Our cities collapsed. There's a difference."</p>
            <p>"We sent aid. Medical teams, engineers-"</p>
            <p>"After. You sent aid after. While the rest of us were burying our dead, you were deciding whether it was cost-effective to help. And then you showed up with care packages and expected us to be grateful."</p>
            <p><em>The medic went quiet. He'd heard this one before. He'd keep hearing it.</em></p>
        """,
        description: """
            <h3>Effects</h3>
            <ul>
                <li>Australia sat at the edge of the map while the world burned and called it luck. No direct Collapse hits, no ground war, no occupation. They showed up after the worst was over with supply shipments and good intentions, and now they walk through the ruins like tourists. You can't take someone seriously who's never had to choose between survival and everything else.</li>
                <li>You gain 3 strife whenever you must take orders from, rely on, or cooperate closely with an Australian.</li>
                <li>The first time this anxiety applies in a scene, you gain 1 fortune point.</li>
            </ul>
        """
    },
    Claustrophobia: {
        type: ["Mental"],
        flavor: """
            <p><em>The elevator was small. Not dangerously small, just normal-building small: four people, fluorescent light, brushed metal walls. The operator stepped in, pressed the button, and immediately started counting floors.</em></p>
            <p>"You okay?"</p>
            <p>"Fine."</p>
            <p><em>Her breathing was measured. Deliberate. The kind of breathing you learn in stress inoculation training, being used in an elevator in a Green Zone office building.</em></p>
            <p>"We could have taken the stairs."</p>
            <p>"It's twelve floors. I'm fine."</p>
            <p><em>The elevator stopped between floors for three seconds while the system processed a call from another level. Her hand found the wall. Her knuckles went white.</em></p>
            <p>"It does that sometimes. Old building."</p>
            <p>"I know what it does."</p>
            <p><em>When the doors opened on twelve, she was out before they finished moving.</em></p>
        """,
        description: """
            <h3>Effects</h3>
            <ul>
                <li>Enclosed spaces compress the air out of your lungs before the walls have moved an inch. Elevators, crawlspaces, vehicle interiors, underground bunkers: your body knows they're traps before your mind can argue otherwise.</li>
                <li>You gain 3 strife whenever you enter or remain in a confined space (elevators, tunnels, sealed vehicles, small rooms without visible exits).</li>
                <li>The first time this anxiety applies in a scene, you gain 1 fortune point.</li>
            </ul>
        """
    },
    Agoraphobia: {
        type: ["Mental"],
        flavor: """
            <p><em>The convoy stopped at the edge of the Purification Zone. Ahead: two kilometers of open ground, flat terrain, no structures. Standard transit. The squad dismounted to stretch their legs. One stayed in the vehicle.</em></p>
            <p>"Kowalski, we're doing a perimeter walk. Come on."</p>
            <p>"I can see the perimeter from here."</p>
            <p>"With binoculars, through a window."</p>
            <p>"That's seeing it."</p>
            <p><em>The squad leader looked at the open field, then back at Kowalski, who was gripping the door handle like it was a safety line.</em></p>
            <p>"This about Volgograd?"</p>
            <p>"This is about the fact that I can do my job from inside the vehicle."</p>
            <p>"Kowalski."</p>
            <p>"Two kilometers of open ground. No cover. No structures. Nothing between me and the sky but air. Tell me what tactical advantage walking out there gives me, and I'll go."</p>
            <p><em>The squad leader didn't have an answer for that. Kowalski stayed in the vehicle.</em></p>
        """,
        description: """
            <h3>Effects</h3>
            <ul>
                <li>Open spaces are kill zones. Wide streets, open fields, rooftops with no railing: every direction is a direction something can come from and there is nowhere to put your back. Rational or not, your body refuses to believe that exposure is safe.</li>
                <li>You gain 3 strife whenever you enter or remain in a wide-open space with no nearby cover or enclosure (open fields, large plazas, exposed rooftops, empty highways).</li>
                <li>The first time this anxiety applies in a scene, you gain 1 fortune point.</li>
            </ul>
        """
    },
    Arachnophobia: {
        type: ["Mental"],
        flavor: """
            <p><em>The forward base was in a repurposed warehouse, and warehouses in Green Zones come with wildlife. The squad had been there two days before the spiders showed up. Small ones, mostly. Cellar spiders in the corners, the occasional wolf spider on the floor. Standard building fauna.</em></p>
            <p><em>Nobody cared. Except Torres.</em></p>
            <p>"There's one in the latrine."</p>
            <p>"So step on it."</p>
            <p>"I'm not going in there."</p>
            <p>"Torres, it's a spider. It's the size of a coin."</p>
            <p>"I can see it from here. It's on the door handle."</p>
            <p><em>Someone went and flicked it away. Torres watched the corner where it landed for ten minutes before going in. She checked every surface twice. When she came out, she checked her boots, her sleeves, and the back of her collar.</em></p>
            <p>"Clear?"</p>
            <p>"Don't."</p>
        """,
        description: """
            <h3>Effects</h3>
            <ul>
                <li>It's the legs. Or the way they move. Or the way they sit perfectly still until they don't. Whatever the reason, spiders and insects trigger a response in you that training hasn't touched. You know they're harmless. Your hands don't care.</li>
                <li>You gain 3 strife whenever you encounter spiders, insects, or similar creatures in your immediate environment, or whenever you must enter a space you know to be infested with them.</li>
