    },
    "Pencil Pusher": {
        type: ["Mental"],
        flavor: """
            <p><em>The Commander needed a volunteer for the recon element. Before she could finish the sentence, the logistics officer spoke up.</em></p>
            <p>"I can handle the after-action paperwork while they're out."</p>
            <p>"I wasn't going to ask you to do paperwork. I was going to ask if you wanted to go."</p>
            <p><em>A pause. The logistics officer looked at the rest of the squad, then back at the Commander.</em></p>
            <p>"I'm more useful here."</p>
            <p>"You qualified on the range last month. Highest marks in the unit."</p>
            <p>"That's a range. This is fieldwork. I'd slow them down."</p>
            <p>"You wouldn't."</p>
            <p><em>She would. She was sure of it. The range was controlled, predictable, something she could prepare for. Fieldwork was chaos, and she was a person who organized chaos into spreadsheets, not someone who walked into it. She'd filed enough casualty reports to know what happened to people who stepped outside their competence.</em></p>
            <p>"I'll have the AARs ready when they get back."</p>
        """,
        description: """
            <h3>Effects</h3>
            <ul>
                <li>Your desk is your foxhole. You know how to file, organize, requisition, and report, and you have convinced yourself that this is the ceiling of your usefulness. Stepping outside that role means risking failure in front of people who already see you as the person who handles the boring parts. Better to be reliably invisible than visibly inadequate.</li>
                <li>You gain 3 strife whenever you are asked to operate outside your administrative comfort zone, whenever you must take initiative in an unfamiliar role, or whenever your paperwork-first instinct is challenged by someone who believes you're capable of more.</li>
                <li>The first time this anxiety applies in a scene, you gain 1 fortune point.</li>
            </ul>
        """
    },
    Ablative: {
        type: ["Mental"],
        flavor: """
            <p><em>The breach plan had a rotation. Everyone takes point in sequence. Fair, even, shared risk. Korin volunteered for every door anyway.</em></p>
            <p>"It's Chen's turn on point."</p>
            <p>"I'll take it."</p>
            <p>"You took the last two."</p>
            <p>"I'm better armored. It makes sense."</p>
            <p>"It makes sense to rotate, which is why we have a rotation."</p>
            <p><em>She took point anyway. Not by arguing, but by being the first one at the door every time, already stacked, already set, making it awkward for anyone else to step in front of her. After the third room, Chen stopped trying.</em></p>
            <p><em>The medic patched three holes in her torso plating afterward. Thirty minutes of work. A human would have been medevaced.</em></p>
            <p>"You know you don't have to do this."</p>
            <p>"This is what I'm for."</p>
            <p>"That's not true."</p>
            <p><em>She looked at the holes in her armor. Thirty minutes to patch. A human would have been medevaced. The math was simple and she was tired of people pretending it wasn't.</em></p>
