        description: """
            <h3>Effects</h3>
            <ul>
                <li>You are durable and replaceable, and you have decided that this makes you the correct person to absorb every hit. You volunteer for point, take rearguard without being asked, and position yourself between danger and everyone else because you believe, with quiet certainty, that this is your only real value. Being protected feels wrong. Being kept safe feels like waste.</li>
                <li>You gain 3 strife whenever you are placed in a non-sacrificial role (protected, kept in reserve, told to stay back), or whenever someone else takes a hit that you believe should have been yours.</li>
                <li>The first time this anxiety applies in a scene, you gain 1 fortune point.</li>
            </ul>
        """
    },
    "Survivor's Guilt": {
        type: ["Mental"],
        flavor: """
            <p><em>The memorial wall in the Green Zone outpost had forty-seven names. She knew eleven of them personally. Three of them had been standing next to her when they died.</em></p>
            <p><em>The squad chaplain found her there at 0300, reading the names again.</em></p>
            <p>"You should be sleeping."</p>
            <p>"Harmon was a better shot than me. Better instincts. Better under pressure."</p>
            <p>"I know."</p>
            <p>"So why am I here and she isn't?"</p>
            <p>"That's not a question with an answer."</p>
            <p>"It has an answer. The answer is that I was standing two meters to the left. That's it. Two meters. The shrapnel went right and I was left and Harmon is on a wall."</p>
            <p><em>The chaplain sat down next to her. He'd had this conversation before. He'd have it again. The names on the wall didn't change, but the people reading them always asked the same question.</em></p>
            <p>"Two meters."</p>
        """,
        description: """
            <h3>Effects</h3>
            <ul>
                <li>You lived and someone else didn't, and there is no reason for it that makes sense. Luck, positioning, timing: none of it justifies why you're still breathing and they aren't. You carry their absence like a weight that gets heavier the further you get from the day it happened.</li>
                <li>You gain 3 strife whenever you are reminded of those you've lost (memorials, similar situations, meeting people who knew them), whenever you survive a situation where others don't, or whenever someone tells you that you deserve to be alive.</li>
                <li>The first time this anxiety applies in a scene, you gain 1 fortune point.</li>
            </ul>
        """
    },
    "Death Wish": {
        type: ["Mental"],
        flavor: """
            <p><em>The route through the Yellow Zone had two options: the road, which was exposed but clear, and the ravine, which was shorter but unmapped and likely mined. The operator chose the ravine without hesitation.</em></p>
            <p>"We're taking the road."</p>
            <p>"Ravine's faster."</p>
            <p>"Ravine's unmapped."</p>
            <p>"So we map it."</p>
            <p>"With what? Your feet?"</p>
            <p>"If that's what it takes."</p>
