    "House of Cards": {
        type: ["Social"],
        flavor: """
            <p><em>The name on her credentials was Mira Sokol. Before that it was Yelena Drava. Before that, someone else. She'd been Mira for two years now, long enough that she sometimes forgot which details belonged to which version of herself.</em></p>
            <p>"Mira, where'd you say you were stationed before this?"</p>
            <p>"Sector 12. Logistics support."</p>
            <p>"Right, right. My cousin was in Sector 12, actually. Supply depot near the eastern checkpoint?"</p>
            <p><em>She didn't hesitate. Hesitation was the first thing to kill a cover.</em></p>
            <p>"Western side. Different compound. Probably never crossed paths."</p>
            <p>"Small world, though. I'll ask her next time we talk."</p>
            <p>"Sure."</p>
            <p><em>That night she updated her cover notes. Added the cousin. Cross-referenced the Sector 12 depot layout from public records. Built a mental map of a compound she'd never set foot in, in case the conversation came up again. It always came up again.</em></p>
        """,
        description: """
            <h3>Effects</h3>
            <ul>
                <li>Your identity is a construction, and you are its full-time maintenance crew. Every casual conversation is a potential structural failure. Every new person who knows your name is another load-bearing lie that has to hold. You've been doing this long enough that the performance is seamless, but the effort never stops.</li>
                <li>You gain 3 strife whenever your cover identity is tested by direct questions, background verification, or encounters with people who might know the real you.</li>
                <li>The first time this anxiety applies in a scene, you gain 1 fortune point.</li>
            </ul>
        """
    },
    Noncommittal: {
        type: ["Interpersonal"],
        flavor: """
            <p><em>They'd been sharing quarters for four months. It started as convenience, became routine, and at some point crossed a line that neither of them had drawn. The other operator finally said it out loud.</em></p>
            <p>"So what are we?"</p>
            <p><em>Silence. The kind that answers the question before anyone speaks.</em></p>
            <p>"We're... this. Whatever this is."</p>
            <p>"That's not an answer."</p>
            <p>"It's the answer I have."</p>
            <p>"I'm asking if I matter to you."</p>
            <p>"You matter to me."</p>
            <p>"Then why can't you say it?"</p>
            <p><em>Because the last person she said it to is in a file somewhere, listed under casualties. Because the person before that walked away clean and never looked back. Because 'partner' is a word that means 'someone who will eventually leave or be taken,' and she has run out of ways to survive that.</em></p>
            <p>"I just... can't."</p>
        """,
        description: """
            <h3>Effects</h3>
            <ul>
                <li>Commitment means giving someone the ability to hurt you, and you have decided (consciously or not) that you will never allow that again. It might be fear of inadequacy, fear of betrayal, or the simple arithmetic of loss in a profession where people don't come home. The result is the same: you keep everyone at arm's length, especially the ones who get close.</li>
                <li>You gain 3 strife whenever someone expresses emotional attachment to you and expects reciprocation, whenever a relationship deepens beyond casual, or whenever you are expected to make a long-term personal commitment.</li>
                <li>The first time this anxiety applies in a scene, you gain 1 fortune point.</li>
            </ul>
        """
    },
    Radphobia: {
        type: ["Mental"],
        flavor: """
            <p><em>The mission route passed through a Purification Zone. Residual readings were well within safe limits: 3 Vebryans, barely above background. The briefing said full transit time was forty minutes. Everyone geared up. One operator put on a full CBRN suit.</em></p>
            <p>"The readings are three Vebryans. You don't need the full kit."</p>
            <p>"Three Vebryans is not zero."</p>
