        """,
        description: """
            <h3>Effects</h3>
            <ul>
                <li>Collapse Radiation is invisible, cumulative, and turns people into things that used to be people. Most will never receive a dangerous dose. You cannot make yourself believe that you are most people. Any reading above zero is too high, any exposure is one exposure closer to the threshold, and no amount of reassurance changes the math in your head.</li>
                <li>You gain 3 strife whenever you enter an area with any measurable Collapse Radiation, whenever protective equipment is unavailable or compromised, or whenever you learn that you've been unknowingly exposed.</li>
                <li>The first time this anxiety applies in a scene, you gain 1 fortune point.</li>
            </ul>
        """
    },
    "Gun Grabber": {
        type: ["Social"],
        flavor: """
            <p><em>The armory inspection was mandatory. Everyone's weapon on the table, field-stripped, catalogued. The operator placed hers down like she was handling medical waste.</em></p>
            <p>"You'd think after ten years you'd be used to it."</p>
            <p>"I'm used to it. That's different from accepting it."</p>
            <p>"It's a tool."</p>
            <p>"It's a tool designed to kill people. We had a chance to get rid of them, and we didn't, and then the world ended and everyone decided that proved them right. It didn't prove them right. It proved we waited too long."</p>
            <p>"There was a world war. What were we supposed to do, ask nicely?"</p>
            <p>"We were supposed to have solved this before it got to a world war. Now every contractor, every militia, every teenager in a Yellow Zone is armed to the teeth and we call it 'security.' Sixty years of progress and the answer is still 'more guns.'"</p>
            <p><em>She reassembled her weapon, passed the inspection, and holstered it with the same expression someone wears while taking unpleasant medicine.</em></p>
        """,
        description: """
            <h3>Effects</h3>
            <ul>
                <li>The world had a chance to disarm and chose not to. The fact that a global catastrophe and a world war happened since then doesn't justify the arms race; it condemns the failure to prevent it. Every sidearm on every hip is a monument to a problem humanity refused to solve, and you carry yours under protest.</li>
                <li>You gain 3 strife whenever you are surrounded by conspicuous armament (weapons markets, heavily armed checkpoints, arsenal briefings), whenever someone glorifies or normalizes weapons culture, or whenever you must use your own weapon.</li>
                <li>The first time this anxiety applies in a scene, you gain 1 fortune point.</li>
            </ul>
        """
    },
    "Second Best": {
        type: ["Mental"],
        flavor: """
            <p><em>The performance review was good. Solid marks across the board. "Reliable." "Consistent." "Valuable team member." She read it twice and felt nothing.</em></p>
            <p>"This is a good review."</p>
            <p>"I know."</p>
            <p>"You don't look like you think it's a good review."</p>
            <p>"Nakov got 'exceptional.' I got 'reliable.'"</p>
            <p>"Reliable is good."</p>
            <p>"Reliable is what you call the backup generator. It's what you call the person you send when the person you wanted isn't available."</p>
            <p>"That's not what it means."</p>
            <p><em>She knew that. Intellectually, she knew that. But every commendation she'd ever received came with the unspoken footnote that someone else would have done it better, faster, more impressively. She was fine. She was always fine. She was never the reason the squad succeeded. She was never the reason it failed. She was reliable.</em></p>
            <p><em>She hated that word.</em></p>
        """,
        description: """
            <h3>Effects</h3>
            <ul>
                <li>You are adequate. Competent. Fine. And the quiet certainty that 'fine' is all you will ever be follows you into every room. Other people have talent, presence, something that makes them matter. You have effort, and effort only gets you so far before the gap becomes visible.</li>
                <li>You gain 3 strife whenever you are directly compared to someone more skilled or accomplished, whenever your contributions are overlooked or attributed to others, or whenever you fail at something publicly.</li>
                <li>The first time this anxiety applies in a scene, you gain 1 fortune point.</li>
            </ul>
        """
    },
    Wallflower: {
        type: ["Social"],
        flavor: """
            <p><em>The squad dinner was supposed to be casual. No ranks, no shop talk, just food and conversation. Most of the squad settled in immediately. One sat at the end of the table, eating quietly, contributing nothing.</em></p>
            <p>"Lin, you're being quiet."</p>
            <p>"I'm eating."</p>
            <p>"You can eat and talk."</p>
            <p><em>She couldn't, actually. Or she could, but the moment she opened her mouth to say something the words would rearrange themselves into something stupid and everyone would look at her and she'd have to deal with that.</em></p>
            <p>"I'm fine."</p>
            <p>"Come sit in the middle, at least."</p>
            <p>"I can hear everyone from here."</p>
            <p><em>She could. She heard every conversation, tracked every topic, had responses to half of them. They stayed in her head, where they were safe, where no one could respond to them, where she didn't have to watch someone's expression shift when she said the wrong thing.</em></p>
